## Conda environments in this repository

| YML file | **Environment name** | Purpose |
|----------|----------------------|---------|
| `envs/environment.yml` | `{{ project_name }}` | Day -to -day development & docs |
| `workflow/envs/py312-workflow.yaml` | `py312-workflow` | Minimal runtime for Snakemake itself |
| `workflow/envs/py312-tox.yaml` | `py312-tox` | Isolated integration tests driven by *tox* |
| *rule -level* envs | autogenerated | Reproducible, conflict -free runtime per rule |

> **Tip:** Snakemake autogenerates the rule -level environments inside
> `.snakemake/conda/`. To pre -solve them all at once run:
>
> ```bash
> snakemake conda_localize
> ```

## 1 Post -install tasks (all platforms)

| Task | Command |
|------|---------|
| **Enable pre -commit** hooks | `pre-commit install` |
| **Solve rule envs in advance** | `snakemake conda_localize` |
| **Run the complete pipeline** | `snakemake --cores 4 --use-conda --conda-frontend mamba` |
| **Generate / live -preview docs** | `snakemake docs` |

## 2 VS Code set -up

All development is optimised for VS Code.  The repository ships with a
curated list of extensions under `.vscode/extensions.json`.

```bash
# Install the list programmatically (requires `jq` and `code` on PATH)
EXT_LIST=$(cat .vscode/extensions.json | jq -r '.[]')
for ext in $EXT_LIST; do
    code --install-extension "$ext"
done
```

### Platform specific setup

- **[Windows → WSL 2](windows.md)** - install the _Remote - WSL_ extension, then
    **Reopen Folder in WSL**.

- **HPC clusters (SLURM)** - launch a VS Code session through
    _Open OnDemand_ (see the [SLURM guide](slurm.md)).
    Your local VS Code client connects via the browser, so the set -up is
    virtually identical to working on a laptop.

## 3. Snakemake workflow setup

```bash
conda env update --name {{ package_name }}-py312-workflow --file workflow/envs/{{ package_name }}-py312-workflow.yaml
```

```bash
conda activate {{ package_name }}-py312-workflow
snakemake conda_localize
```

